  "datePublished": "2026-03-03",
  "description": "Second-order cybernetics is the branch of cybernetics that includes the observer within the system being observed. Where first-order cybernetics (Norbert Wiener, W. Ross Ashby) studies systems from outside — describing feedback loops, stability conditions, and regulatory mechanisms as if the analyst stands apart — second-order cybernetics recognizes that the observer is always part of what they describe.\nHeinz von Foerster pioneered this reflexive turn, most fully in Observing Systems (1981) [cite:@vonfoerster_ObservingSystems_1981]. Von Foerster emphasized that observation is not passive recording but active construction: the distinctions an observer draws are operations performed by a system with its own structure, limitations, and blind spots. Every act of description is simultaneously an act of self-organization by the describing system. This does not collapse into relativism — some descriptions remain more productive than others — but it forecloses the possibility of a view from nowhere.\n",
  "name": "Second-Order Cybernetics",
